<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>

<div id="r-in-5-minutes" class="section level1">
<h1>R in 5 minutes</h1>
<p>R is a interactive scripting language. R scripts have the file
extension <code>.R</code> or <code>.r</code>, and scripts can be run
“start-to-finish” from the command line,
e.g. <code>Rscript helloworld.R</code>, similar to Python.</p>
<p>It is more common to use R <em>interactively</em>, generally with the
help of R Studio or a similar IDE. Run a single line of R code using
<code>ctrl-enter</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>5 + (5 / 2)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 7.5</code></pre>
<div id="vectors" class="section level3">
<h3>Vectors</h3>
<p>Assign a vector of numbers to a <em>variable</em> called
<code>v</code>. The assignment operator can be inserted with
<code>alt+-</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>v &lt;- c(1, 2, 3)</code></pre>
<p>We can now access this vector by referring to <code>v</code> in our
script. For example, we can access specific contents of the vector</p>
<pre class="r"><code>v[3] + 2</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 5</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>v[-2]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1 3</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>v[c(1, 1, 3)] # &quot;multiple indexing&quot; using another vector</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 1 1 3</code></pre>
<p>Notice that the contents of <code>v</code> are unchanged. Assign new
contents to <code>v</code> like so.</p>
<pre class="r"><code># change an item
v[2] &lt;- -1 
# append new item
(v &lt;- c(v, 4)) # print the results of an assignment using ()</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]  1 -1  3  4</code></pre>
<div class="warning">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Warning</strong></p>
</div>
<p>Appending to a vector in this way is very inefficient in R compared
to other languages. Avoid building up large lists in this way.</p>
</div>
<div id="vectorized-operations" class="section level4">
<h4>Vectorized operations</h4>
<p>An important defining feature of R is that many operations are
automatically <em>vectorized</em>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>v &lt;- 1:5
v + 1 # 1 is &quot;recycled&quot; and applied to each element</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 2 3 4 5 6</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>v + 1:length(v)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]  2  4  6  8 10</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>v + c(1, 2) # a 2-vector can not be applied to a 5-vector with recycling</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning in v + c(1, 2): longer object length is not a multiple of shorter object
## length</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 2 4 4 6 6</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>v[-5] + c(1, 2) # but it can be applied to a 4-vector</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 2 4 4 6</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>sin(v)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]  0.8414710  0.9092974  0.1411200 -0.7568025 -0.9589243</code></pre>
<div class="warning">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Warning</strong></p>
</div>
<p>A common source of errors is using vectorization unintentionally,
especially with recycled elements. Try to become aware of which R
functions use vectorization.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="types-and-lists" class="section level3">
<h3>Types and lists</h3>
<p>The major type distinctions in R are <em>character</em>,
<em>numeric</em>, <em>logical</em>, and <em>NULL</em>. Some
comments:</p>
<ul>
<li>Strings and characters are equivalent, and can be created using
<code>&quot;...&quot;</code> or <code>&#39;...&#39;</code></li>
<li>Numerics include doubles like 3.1415927 and integers like
<code>3L</code></li>
<li>Logical objects are either <code>TRUE</code>, <code>FALSE</code> and
<code>NA</code></li>
<li>The <code>NULL</code> object is the unique “nothing” object, of
length zero</li>
</ul>
<p>Vectors can <strong>only</strong> contain a single type. Vector types
are promoted eagerly.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>v[2] &lt;- 3.5
v[3] &lt;- &quot;foo&quot;</code></pre>
<p>Lists are like vectors, but <em>can</em> contain multiple types.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>v &lt;- 1:5
l &lt;- as.list(v)
l[[2]] &lt;- 3L
l[3:4] &lt;- list(FALSE, list(&quot;bar&quot;, &quot;bat&quot;))
l</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [[1]]
## [1] 1
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] 3
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] FALSE
## 
## [[4]]
## [[4]][[1]]
## [1] &quot;bar&quot;
## 
## [[4]][[2]]
## [1] &quot;bat&quot;
## 
## 
## [[5]]
## [1] 5</code></pre>
<p>Both vectors and lists can be <em>named</em>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>names(v) &lt;- letters[1:5]; v</code></pre>
<pre><code>## a b c d e 
## 1 2 3 4 5</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="dataframes" class="section level3">
<h3>Dataframes</h3>
<p>A dataframe is like an excel file in code. It is a 2-dimensional
array with named columns.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>data(&quot;mtcars&quot;) # simultaneously load mtcars data and assign to variable with same name
mtcars</code></pre>
<pre><code>##                      mpg cyl  disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4           21.0   6 160.0 110 3.90 2.620 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Mazda RX4 Wag       21.0   6 160.0 110 3.90 2.875 17.02  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710          22.8   4 108.0  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive      21.4   6 258.0 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout   18.7   8 360.0 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant             18.1   6 225.0 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1
## Duster 360          14.3   8 360.0 245 3.21 3.570 15.84  0  0    3    4
## Merc 240D           24.4   4 146.7  62 3.69 3.190 20.00  1  0    4    2
## Merc 230            22.8   4 140.8  95 3.92 3.150 22.90  1  0    4    2
## Merc 280            19.2   6 167.6 123 3.92 3.440 18.30  1  0    4    4

## Merc 450SE          16.4   8 275.8 180 3.07 4.070 17.40  0  0    3    3
## Merc 450SL          17.3   8 275.8 180 3.07 3.730 17.60  0  0    3    3
## Merc 450SLC         15.2   8 275.8 180 3.07 3.780 18.00  0  0    3    3

## Camaro Z28          13.3   8 350.0 245 3.73 3.840 15.41  0  0    3    4
## Pontiac Firebird    19.2   8 400.0 175 3.08 3.845 17.05  0  0    3    2
## Fiat X1-9           27.3   4  79.0  66 4.08 1.935 18.90  1  1    4    1
## Porsche 914-2       26.0   4 120.3  91 4.43 2.140 16.70  0  1    5    2
## Lotus Europa        30.4   4  95.1 113 3.77 1.513 16.90  1  1    5    2
## Ford Pantera L      15.8   8 351.0 264 4.22 3.170 14.50  0  1    5    4
## Ferrari Dino        19.7   6 145.0 175 3.62 2.770 15.50  0  1    5    6
## Maserati Bora       15.0   8 301.0 335 3.54 3.570 14.60  0  1    5    8
## Volvo 142E          21.4   4 121.0 109 4.11 2.780 18.60  1  1    4    2</code></pre>
<p>We will work with tabular data a lot in a moment. For now, here are
some basic operations.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mtcars[,3] # contents of third column</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  [1] 160.0 160.0 108.0 258.0 360.0 225.0 360.0 146.7 140.8 167.6 167.6 275.8
## [13] 275.8 275.8 472.0 460.0 440.0  78.7  75.7  71.1 120.1 318.0 304.0 350.0
## [25] 400.0  79.0 120.3  95.1 351.0 145.0 301.0 121.0</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>mtcars[c(1, 3, 5),] # subset rows</code></pre>
<pre><code>##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat   wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4         21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.62 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.32 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.44 17.02  0  0    3    2</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>summary(mtcars)</code></pre>
<pre><code>##       mpg             cyl             disp             hp       
##  Min.   :10.40   Min.   :4.000   Min.   : 71.1   Min.   : 52.0

<div class="info">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Info</strong></p>
</div>
<p>Most R objects have implemented their own <code>summary</code>
function, including those provided by other packages. The output will
depend on the nature of the object.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="installing-and-loading-packages" class="section level3">
<h3>Installing and loading packages</h3>
<p>Packages are an essential part of the R workflow. They are what makes
the open-source, community-driven R ecosystem so diverse and up-to-date
with the latest research.</p>
<p>Install a new package with
<code>install.packages(&quot;&lt;package name&gt;&quot;)</code>, and load a
package with <code>library(&lt;package name&gt;)</code>.</p>
</div>
<div id="the-long-version" class="section level3">
<h3>The long version</h3>
<p>If you want to learn more about R in general, here are some
resources. However, we will cover many of these basics in the following
hands-on tutorial.</p>
<ul>
<li>The official R manual for the most recent version of R is <a href="cran.r-project.org/manuals.html">here</a></li>
<li>For quick examples of a large number of functions in base R, see
Learn X in Y Minutes’ <a href="https://learnxinyminutes.com/docs/r/">post</a>.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="the-tidyverse-packages" class="section level1">
<h1>The <code>tidyverse</code> packages</h1>
<p>From the website:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The tidyverse is an opinionated collection of R packages designed for
data science. All packages share an underlying design philosophy,
grammar, and data structures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The “core” tidyverse packages are the ones automatically
installed/loaded:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(tidyverse)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## ── Attaching packages ─────────────────────────────────────── tidyverse 1.3.1 ──</code></pre>
<pre><code>## ✔ ggplot2 3.3.5     ✔ purrr   0.3.4
## ✔ tibble  3.1.7     ✔ dplyr   1.0.9
## ✔ tidyr   1.1.4     ✔ stringr 1.4.0
## ✔ readr   2.1.1     ✔ forcats 0.5.1</code></pre>
<pre><code>## ── Conflicts ────────────────────────────────────────── tidyverse_conflicts() ──
## ✖ dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## ✖ dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()</code></pre>
<p>They form a <a href="https://www.tidyverse.org/packages/">complete
workflow</a> for writing most R programs:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>readr</code> for reading/writing tabular data</li>
<li><code>tidyr</code> for cleaning and organizing data into a “tidy”
format</li>
<li><code>dplyr</code> and <code>purrr</code> for manipulating and
summarizing</li>
<li><code>forcats</code> and <code>stringr</code> for special operations
on factors and strings, respectively</li>
</ul>
<p>In addition to these core packages, other more specific packages are
considered part of the “extended” tidyverse. These packages need to be
installed/loaded independently.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(tidygraph)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## 
## Attaching package: &#39;tidygraph&#39;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## The following object is masked from &#39;package:stats&#39;:
## 
##     filter</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>library(ggraph)</code></pre>
<div id="learning-resources" class="section level3">
<h3>Learning resources</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><a href="https://www.rstudio.com/resources/cheatsheets/">Cheatsheets</a>
are a great way to learn a package quickly. I also like to use them to
learn a package while working. I’ll pull up the package I want to learn,
and try to find ways to use different functions from it for whatever I’m
doing.</p></li>
<li><p><a href="https://r4ds.had.co.nz/index.html">R for Data
Science</a> (R4DS) can be good for all levels, and centers around the
tidyverse. It starts very gently and assumes almost no R knowledge.
There are also exercises and solutions available.</p></li>
<li><p><a href="https://adv-r.hadley.nz/index.html">Advanced R</a> is a
more general programming guide, but draws heavily from tidyverse
packages.</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="tidy-data-the-tibble-and-tidyr-packages" class="section level1">
<h1>Tidy data: the <code>tibble</code> and <code>tidyr</code>
packages</h1>
<p>The most fundamental data structure for tidyverse is a modernization
of the dataframe. The most important differences are clearer printing
and more flexible column names.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 87 × 14
##    name     height  mass hair_color skin_color eye_color birth_year sex   gender
##    &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;int&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;      &lt;chr&gt;      &lt;chr&gt;          &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;chr&gt; 
##  1 Luke Sk…    172    77 blond      fair       blue            19   male  mascu…
##  2 C-3PO       167    75 &lt;NA&gt;       gold       yellow         112   none  mascu…
##  3 R2-D2        96    32 &lt;NA&gt;       white, bl… red             33   none  mascu…
##  4 Darth V…    202   136 none       white      yellow          41.9 male  mascu…
##  5 Leia Or…    150    49 brown      light      brown           19   fema… femin…
##  6 Owen La…    178   120 brown, gr… light      blue            52   male  mascu…
##  7 Beru Wh…    165    75 brown      light      blue            47   fema… femin…
##  8 R5-D4        97    32 &lt;NA&gt;       white, red red             NA   none  mascu…
##  9 Biggs D…    183    84 black      light      brown           24   male  mascu…
## 10 Obi-Wan…    182    77 auburn, w… fair       blue-gray       57   male  mascu…
## # … with 77 more rows, and 5 more variables: homeworld &lt;chr&gt;, species &lt;chr&gt;,
## #   films &lt;list&gt;, vehicles &lt;list&gt;, starships &lt;list&gt;</code></pre>
<p>Compared to a <code>data.frame</code>, a <code>tibble</code> is
printed in a truncated format by default. Notice also the dimension of
the data, the inferred types of each column, and the dimension of each
list-columns (the <code>starship</code> column for example) are also
printed.</p>
<div id="creating-tibbles" class="section level3">
<h3>Creating tibbles</h3>
<p>Creating tibbles from scratch can be done similar to
<code>data.frame</code>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>tibble(x = 1:5, y = LETTERS[1:5], z = x^2)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 × 3
##       x y         z
##   &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1     1 A         1
## 2     2 B         4
## 3     3 C         9
## 4     4 D        16
## 5     5 E        25</code></pre>
<p>or with <code>tribble</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>tribble(
  ~x, ~y,
  1, &#39;A&#39;,
  2, &#39;B&#39;,
  3, &#39;C&#39;
)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##       x y    
##   &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;
## 1     1 A    
## 2     2 B    
## 3     3 C</code></pre>
<div class="info">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Info</strong></p>
</div>
<p>The <code>readr</code> functions such as <code>read_csv</code> always
return a tibble</p>
</div>
<p>Creating tibbles from dataframes, matrices, or named vectors:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>m &lt;- matrix(1:10, ncol=2)
as_tibble(m)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##      V1    V2
##   &lt;int&gt; &lt;int&gt;
## 1     1     6
## 2     2     7
## 3     3     8
## 4     4     9
## 5     5    10</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>x &lt;- c(a = 1, b = 2, c = 3)
enframe(x)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##   name  value
##   &lt;chr&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 a         1
## 2 b         2
## 3 c         3</code></pre>
<p>You can largely use tibbles and dataframes interchangeably (functions
that say they work with one will work with the other), so I’ll just call
them dataframes from now on. See the vignette for more features and
differences from regular dataframes.</p>
<pre><code>vignette(&#39;tibble&#39;)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="what-makes-data-tidy" class="section level3">
<h3>What makes data “tidy”?</h3>
<p><a href="https://r4ds.had.co.nz/tidy-data.html">R for Data
Science</a> gives three rules for tidy data:</p>
<blockquote>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>Each variable has its own column</li>
<li>Each observation has its own row</li>
<li>Each value must have its own cell</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p>The <code>tidyr</code> package contains functions for making data
tidy. For example, suppose you are given some data from a field
survey.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>survey &lt;- tibble(
  present_yes = sample(c(&#39;yes&#39;, NA), 15, replace = TRUE),
  present_no = ifelse(is.na(present_yes), &#39;no&#39;, NA),
  visit_id = 1:15
)

survey</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 15 × 3
##    present_yes present_no visit_id
##    &lt;chr&gt;       &lt;chr&gt;         &lt;int&gt;
##  1 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              1
##  2 &lt;NA&gt;        no                2
##  3 &lt;NA&gt;        no                3
##  4 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              4
##  5 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              5
##  6 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              6
##  7 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              7
##  8 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              8
##  9 yes         &lt;NA&gt;              9
## 10 yes         &lt;NA&gt;             10
## 11 yes         &lt;NA&gt;             11
## 12 yes         &lt;NA&gt;             12
## 13 &lt;NA&gt;        no               13
## 14 &lt;NA&gt;        no               14
## 15 &lt;NA&gt;        no               15</code></pre>
<p>Someone has spread a single variable over two columns, causing lots
of blank spaces in the data. This may have been more convenient in the
field, but programming with the data as-is will be a bit difficult.
Thankfully, conversion to tidy format is easy.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>unite(survey, &#39;present&#39;, present_yes, present_no, na.rm = TRUE)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 15 × 2
##    present visit_id
##    &lt;chr&gt;      &lt;int&gt;
##  1 yes            1
##  2 no             2
##  3 no             3
##  4 yes            4
##  5 yes            5
##  6 yes            6
##  7 yes            7
##  8 yes            8
##  9 yes            9
## 10 yes           10
## 11 yes           11
## 12 yes           12
## 13 no            13
## 14 no            14
## 15 no            15</code></pre>
<p>Here, we have used <code>unite</code>, which pastes two or more
columns of strings into a single column, while removing the
<code>NA</code>s.</p>
<p>Another nice function is to drop rows which contain an
<code>NA</code>, possibly only in specific columns.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>nrow(starwars)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 87</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>nrow(drop_na(starwars)) # drop all rows with an NA</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 6</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>nrow(drop_na(starwars, birth_year)) # only rows with NA in &quot;birth_year&quot;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 43</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="manipulating-tabular-data-with-dplyr" class="section level1">
<h1>Manipulating tabular data with <code>dplyr</code></h1>
<p>The <code>dplyr</code> package is great for performing seemingly
endless operations on dataframes. Just like in base R, we can subset a
dataframe by rows or columns:</p>
<pre class="r"><code># select specific cols
select(starwars, height, 6)
select(starwars, name:skin_color)

# select last 5 rows
slice_tail(starwars, n = 5)

# all cols with an underscore
select(starwars, contains(&#39;_&#39;))</code></pre>
<p>More complex slicing and subsetting is possible</p>
<pre class="r"><code># select cols conditionally
select(starwars, where(is.double))
select(starwars, !last_col() &amp; ends_with(&#39;s&#39;))

# slice rows conditionally (filtering)
filter(starwars, eye_color == &#39;blue&#39;)</code></pre>
<div id="the-pipe-operator" class="section level3">
<h3>The pipe operator</h3>
<p>Notice that most tidyverse functions are verbs or adverbs (coding is,
after all, just giving instructions). There is a special operator, the
<em>pipe</em> operator, which allows these commands to be chained
together!</p>
<p>As an example, let’s create a random “population” of 1,000 of the
starwars characters:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars |&gt; # start of chain is the data
  filter(eye_color == &#39;blue&#39;) |&gt; # each step takes the previous result
  select(height:species) |&gt; # and does a new thing to it
  slice_sample(n = 1000, replace = TRUE)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1,000 × 10
##    height  mass hair_color   skin_color eye_color birth_year sex    gender   
##     &lt;int&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;        &lt;chr&gt;      &lt;chr&gt;          &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;  &lt;chr&gt;    
##  1    183    NA brown        fair       blue              NA &lt;NA&gt;   &lt;NA&gt;     
##  2    166    50 black        yellow     blue              40 female feminine 
##  3    234   136 brown        brown      blue              NA male   masculine
##  4    175    79 none         light      blue              37 male   masculine
##  5    183    NA brown        fair       blue              82 male   masculine
##  6    183    NA brown        fair       blue              82 male   masculine
##  7    180    NA auburn, grey fair       blue              64 male   masculine
##  8    165    75 brown        light      blue              47 female feminine 
##  9    183    NA brown        fair       blue              82 male   masculine
## 10    178   120 brown, grey  light      blue              52 male   masculine
## # … with 990 more rows, and 2 more variables: homeworld &lt;chr&gt;, species &lt;chr&gt;</code></pre>
<div class="info">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Info</strong></p>
</div>
<p><code>x |&gt; f |&gt; g</code> is the same as <code>g(f(x))</code>;
however, when you string a lot of functions together piping makes things
more readable.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="mutate-summarize-and-count" class="section level3">
<h3>Mutate, summarize, and count</h3>
<p>Another family of <code>dplyr</code> functions use existing columns
to make new ones. The most common is <code>mutate</code>, which appends
a new row based on a vectorized function of existing rows.
<code>transmute</code> is like <code>mutate</code> but only the new
columns are kept.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars |&gt;
  transmute(mass_per_cm = mass / height) # divide mass column by height column</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 87 × 1
##    mass_per_cm
##          &lt;dbl&gt;
##  1       0.448
##  2       0.449
##  3       0.333
##  4       0.673
##  5       0.327
##  6       0.674
##  7       0.455
##  8       0.330
##  9       0.459
## 10       0.423
## # … with 77 more rows</code></pre>
<p>This function, like many others, is often useful to apply separately
to different <em>groups</em> in the data. Suppose we want to assign each
character a unique id based on their homeworld:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars |&gt;
  group_by(homeworld) |&gt;
  mutate(world_id = str_c(homeworld, &#39;_&#39;, 1:n())) |&gt; # n() is short for group size
  pull(world_id) # convert column &quot;world_id&quot; to a vector</code></pre>
<pre><code>##  [1] &quot;Tatooine_1&quot;       &quot;Tatooine_2&quot;       &quot;Naboo_1&quot;          &quot;Tatooine_3&quot;      
##  [5] &quot;Alderaan_1&quot;       &quot;Tatooine_4&quot;       &quot;Tatooine_5&quot;       &quot;Tatooine_6&quot;      
##  [9] &quot;Tatooine_7&quot;       &quot;Stewjon_1&quot;        &quot;Tatooine_8&quot;       &quot;Eriadu_1&quot;        
## [13] &quot;Kashyyyk_1&quot;       &quot;Corellia_1&quot;       &quot;Rodia_1&quot;          &quot;Nal Hutta_1&quot;     
## [17] &quot;Corellia_2&quot;       &quot;Bestine IV_1&quot;     NA                 &quot;Naboo_2&quot;         
## [21] &quot;Kamino_1&quot;         NA                 &quot;Trandosha_1&quot;      &quot;Socorro_1&quot;       
## [25] &quot;Bespin_1&quot;         &quot;Mon Cala_1&quot;       &quot;Chandrila_1&quot;      NA                
## [29] &quot;Endor_1&quot;          &quot;Sullust_1&quot;        NA                 &quot;Cato Neimoidia_1&quot;
## [33] &quot;Coruscant_1&quot;      &quot;Naboo_3&quot;          &quot;Naboo_4&quot;          &quot;Naboo_5&quot;         
## [37] &quot;Naboo_6&quot;          &quot;Toydaria_1&quot;       &quot;Malastare_1&quot;      &quot;Naboo_7&quot;         
## [41] &quot;Tatooine_9&quot;       &quot;Dathomir_1&quot;       &quot;Ryloth_1&quot;         &quot;Ryloth_2&quot;        
## [45] &quot;Vulpter_1&quot;        &quot;Troiken_1&quot;        &quot;Tund_1&quot;           &quot;Haruun Kal_1&quot;    
## [49] &quot;Cerea_1&quot;          &quot;Glee Anselm_1&quot;    &quot;Iridonia_1&quot;       &quot;Coruscant_2&quot;     
## [53] &quot;Iktotch_1&quot;        &quot;Quermia_1&quot;        &quot;Dorin_1&quot;          &quot;Champala_1&quot;      
## [57] &quot;Naboo_8&quot;          &quot;Naboo_9&quot;          &quot;Tatooine_10&quot;      &quot;Geonosis_1&quot;      
## [61] &quot;Mirial_1&quot;         &quot;Mirial_2&quot;         &quot;Naboo_10&quot;         &quot;Serenno_1&quot;       
## [65] &quot;Alderaan_2&quot;       &quot;Concord Dawn_1&quot;   &quot;Zolan_1&quot;          &quot;Ojom_1&quot;          
## [69] &quot;Kamino_2&quot;         &quot;Kamino_3&quot;         &quot;Coruscant_3&quot;      &quot;Aleen Minor_1&quot;   
## [73] NA                 &quot;Skako_1&quot;          &quot;Muunilinst_1&quot;     &quot;Shili_1&quot;         
## [77] &quot;Kalee_1&quot;          &quot;Kashyyyk_2&quot;       &quot;Alderaan_3&quot;       &quot;Umbara_1&quot;        
## [81] &quot;Utapau_1&quot;         NA                 NA                 NA                
## [85] NA                 NA                 &quot;Naboo_11&quot;</code></pre>
<div class="warning">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Warning</strong></p>
</div>
<p>Here, the behavior of <code>str_c</code> shows us that
<strong><code>mutate</code> and many other dplyr verbs operate on
vectors, not individual cells.</strong></p>
</div>
<p>Grouping is frequently used with <code>summarize</code>. Summarizing
is a form of reduction; it takes a (grouped) dataframe and returns a new
dataframe with one row per group:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars |&gt;
    group_by(gender) |&gt;
    drop_na(height) |&gt; # remove NAs from height for mean and sd
    summarize(m_height = mean(height), sd_height = sd(height))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 3 × 3
##   gender    m_height sd_height
##   &lt;chr&gt;        &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 feminine      165.     23.6 
## 2 masculine     177.     37.6 
## 3 &lt;NA&gt;          181.      2.89</code></pre>
<p>Grouping is not just for summarizing. We have seen it can be useful
with mutate, and it is useful with <code>slice_*</code> and
<code>filter</code> as well. Let’s take a random sample of five
characters from each species, first removing rows with less than 5
characters sharing their <code>homeworld</code>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars |&gt;
    group_by(homeworld) |&gt;
    mutate(count = n()) |&gt; 
    filter(count &gt;= 5) |&gt; 
    slice_sample(n = 5)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 15 × 15
## # Groups:   homeworld [3]
##    name     height  mass hair_color skin_color eye_color birth_year sex   gender
##    &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;int&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;      &lt;chr&gt;      &lt;chr&gt;          &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;chr&gt; 
##  1 Jar Jar…    196    66 none       orange     orange          52   male  mascu…
##  2 Dormé       165    NA brown      light      brown           NA   fema… femin…
##  3 Ric Olié    183    NA brown      fair       blue            NA   &lt;NA&gt;  &lt;NA&gt;  
##  4 Cordé       157    NA brown      light      brown           NA   fema… femin…
##  5 Gregar …    185    85 black      dark       brown           NA   male  mascu…
##  6 Owen La…    178   120 brown, gr… light      blue            52   male  mascu…
##  7 Beru Wh…    165    75 brown      light      blue            47   fema… femin…
##  8 Cliegg …    183    NA brown      fair       blue            82   male  mascu…
##  9 Darth V…    202   136 none       white      yellow          41.9 male  mascu…
## 10 Luke Sk…    172    77 blond      fair       blue            19   male  mascu…
## 11 Captain…     NA    NA unknown    unknown    unknown         NA   &lt;NA&gt;  &lt;NA&gt;  
## 12 Finn         NA    NA black      dark       dark            NA   male  mascu…
## 13 IG-88       200   140 none       metal      red             15   none  mascu…
## 14 Rey          NA    NA brown      light      hazel           NA   fema… femin…
## 15 Yoda         66    17 white      green      brown          896   male  mascu…
## # … with 6 more variables: homeworld &lt;chr&gt;, species &lt;chr&gt;, films &lt;list&gt;,
## #   vehicles &lt;list&gt;, starships &lt;list&gt;, count &lt;int&gt;</code></pre>
<p>Finally, the <code>count</code> function is for the common
summarizing task of counting groups:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>count(starwars, homeworld, sort = TRUE)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 49 × 2
##    homeworld     n
##    &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;int&gt;
##  1 Naboo        11
##  2 Tatooine     10
##  3 &lt;NA&gt;         10
##  4 Alderaan      3
##  5 Coruscant     3
##  6 Kamino        3
##  7 Corellia      2
##  8 Kashyyyk      2
##  9 Mirial        2
## 10 Ryloth        2
## # … with 39 more rows</code></pre>
<div class="info">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Info</strong></p>
</div>
<p>Count group interactions by providing &gt;1 column name, and use
<code>add_count</code> to add the counts to the existing data.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="excercises" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Excercises</h3>
<p><code>midwest</code> is a dataset of county-level demographic
information in the Midwestern US. Consider any/all of the following
tasks:</p>
<div id="questions" class="section level4">
<h4>Questions</h4>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>What are the dimensions of <code>midwest</code>?</li>
<li>Use a function from the <code>slice_*</code> family (type
<code>?slice</code> into your console) to find the 50 counties with the
largest <code>popdensity</code>. Now, how many times is each state
represented in this top sample?</li>
<li>Considering only counties in a metro area
(i.e. <code>inmetro == 1</code>), compute the percentage of people below
the poverty line for each state. Also compute the variance.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="solutions" class="section level4">
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>dim(midwest)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 437  28</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>midwest |&gt; 
    slice_max(popdensity, n=50) |&gt; 
    count(state)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 × 2
##   state     n
##   &lt;chr&gt; &lt;int&gt;
## 1 IL       10
## 2 IN        9
## 3 MI       10
## 4 OH       16
## 5 WI        5</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>midwest |&gt; 
    filter(inmetro == 1) |&gt; 
    group_by(state) |&gt; 
    summarize(mpov = mean(percbelowpoverty), vpov = var(percbelowpoverty))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 × 3
##   state  mpov  vpov
##   &lt;chr&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 IL     9.56  15.4
## 2 IN     9.59  16.0
## 3 MI    11.3   18.5
## 4 OH    11.5   15.1
## 5 WI     9.01  16.5</code></pre>
</div>
</div>

<div id="some-other-important-concepts" class="section level1">
<h1>Some other important concepts</h1>
<div id="nesting-and-unnesting" class="section level3">
<h3>Nesting and unnesting</h3>
<p>One of our definitions of tidy data is “one observation per row.”
What exactly is an observation? It depends!</p>
<p>This is why tidy data frequently contains columns with many
“repeated” entries; we want each unit of analysis to be in its own row,
even if it means other variables are repeated when they are shared
across units.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sw_film &lt;- starwars |&gt; 
    unnest(c(films)) |&gt; # rows corresponding to the nested entry are repeated
    select(name, films, everything()) # just move films to front to emphasize we are interested in it
    
sw_film |&gt; 
    group_by(films) |&gt; 
    summarise(m_age = mean(birth_year, na.rm=TRUE)) |&gt; 
    arrange(desc(m_age))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 7 × 2
##   films                   m_age
##   &lt;chr&gt;                   &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 The Phantom Menace      140. 
## 2 Return of the Jedi      133. 
## 3 The Empire Strikes Back 105. 
## 4 Revenge of the Sith     103. 
## 5 Attack of the Clones     98.7
## 6 A New Hope               90.9
## 7 The Force Awakens        56.8</code></pre>
<p>The reason why the tidy version was easier in this case is because in
the original format, our variable of interest was not easily accessible.
If we wanted to make a running tally of <code>birth_year</code> by film,
we would need to use a double for-loop to check which films each
character was in.</p>
<p>When would we deliberately nest for tidy data? One example is when
the observable of interest depends on a subset of the data:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>get_slope &lt;- function(df) lm(height ~ mass, df)$coefficients[2]

starwars |&gt; 
    select(sex, height, mass) |&gt; 
    drop_na(height, mass) |&gt; # remove characters with unknown height/weight
    nest(data = c(height, mass)) |&gt; 
    rowwise() |&gt; 
    mutate(slope = get_slope(data))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 5 × 3
## # Rowwise: 
##   sex            data                slope
##   &lt;chr&gt;          &lt;list&gt;              &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 male           &lt;tibble [44 × 2]&gt;  1.03  
## 2 none           &lt;tibble [4 × 2]&gt;   0.978 
## 3 female         &lt;tibble [9 × 2]&gt;   0.0578
## 4 hermaphroditic &lt;tibble [1 × 2]&gt;  NA     
## 5 &lt;NA&gt;           &lt;tibble [1 × 2]&gt;  NA</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="pivoting" class="section level3">
<h3>Pivoting</h3>
<p>As we will see soon, plotting is another case where the ambiguity of
“variable” and “observation” matters. For this and other cases, there
are ways to <em>pivot</em> the data, changing the context of variables
and observations.</p>
<p>Similar to nesting, think of <code>pivot_longer</code> as lengthening
the dataframe. Rather than every variable getting a row of values, we
make one row of the variables and one of the values:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x &lt;- tribble(
  ~A, ~B, ~C,
  1, 2, 3,
  4, 5, 6
)

x</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 2 × 3
##       A     B     C
##   &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1     1     2     3
## 2     4     5     6</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>pivot_longer(x, everything())</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   name  value
##   &lt;chr&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 A         1
## 2 B         2
## 3 C         3
## 4 A         4
## 5 B         5
## 6 C         6</code></pre>
<p>An example with data, counting how many times each color appears
anywhere:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>starwars |&gt;
  pivot_longer(
    hair_color:eye_color, 
    names_to=&#39;attribute&#39;, 
    values_to=&#39;color&#39;
  ) |&gt;
  count(color)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 44 × 2
##    color             n
##    &lt;chr&gt;         &lt;int&gt;
##  1 auburn            1
##  2 auburn, grey      1
##  3 auburn, white     1
##  4 black            23
##  5 blond             3
##  6 blonde            1
##  7 blue             21
##  8 blue-gray         1
##  9 blue, grey        2
## 10 brown            43
## # … with 34 more rows</code></pre>
<p>Here, since we want to count colors across several columns, we pivot
these columns into a single column and then <code>count</code> it.</p>
</div>
<div id="excercises-1" class="section level3 tabset">
<h3 class="tabset">Excercises</h3>
<div id="questions-1" class="section level4">
<h4>Questions</h4>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p><code>who</code> contains data on country-wide tuberculosis
numbers by year. Columns starting with “new” are counts from that year
for various groups. Using <code>pivot_longer</code>, count the number of
times each country has an <code>NA</code> in one of these columns. Which
countries had the most and least amount of missing data? Why was
pivoting helpful in this example?</p></li>
<li><p><code>us_rent_income</code> contains data on each state’s median
monthly rent and income for 2017. Use <code>pivot_wider</code> to spread
these values into two columns <code>income</code> and <code>rent</code>.
Using these two columns, find the correlation between rent and
income.</p></li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="solutions-1" class="section level4">
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<pre class="r"><code>who |&gt;
    pivot_longer(contains(&quot;new&quot;)) |&gt; 
    group_by(country) |&gt; 
    summarize(na_ct = sum(is.na(value))) |&gt; 
    filter(na_ct %in% c(min(na_ct), max(na_ct)))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 3 × 2
##   country                           na_ct
##   &lt;chr&gt;                             &lt;int&gt;
## 1 Bonaire, Saint Eustatius and Saba    84
## 2 Curacao                              84
## 3 Monaco                             1889</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>us_rent_income |&gt; 
    pivot_wider(GEOID:NAME, names_from = variable, values_from = estimate) |&gt;
    summarize(corr = cor(income, rent, use = &quot;complete.obs&quot;))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##    corr
##   &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 0.741</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="plotting-with-ggplot2" class="section level1">
<h1>Plotting with <code>ggplot2</code></h1>
<p>Some of you may have used <code>ggplot2</code> before. The package
has its own philosophy (the “grammar of graphics”) that builds on those
of all tidyverse packages and tidy data. Let’s go over a few to help
make sense of how <code>ggplot2</code> works:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Plots are made of <em>layers</em>. For ggplot, visual information
is added to plots one “group” at a time, using <em>geometries</em>. For
example, use <code>geom_point</code> to add points and
<code>geom_histrogram</code> to add histogram bins. Multiple types of
geometries can be layered onto the same plot.</p></li>
<li><p>Plots are an interpretation of relationships in the data. These
relationships can be specified with <em>aesthetic mappings</em>. For
example, if the points you are plotting come from two species, you can
color points according to their species with the mapping
<code>species -&gt; color</code>.</p></li>
<li><p>A plot is an object that we can perform operations on. This means
we can always continue to modify a plot by performing new steps, much
like how the <code>|&gt;</code> operator lets data be modified in single
steps. For example, <code>scale_x_sqrt</code> adds the instruction to
take the square root of the variable on the x-axis before plotting. This
also means that <code>ggplot2</code> objects can be stored in a variable
in R to be used later.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Here’s a simple example to see each of these ideas at work:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>gg &lt;- ggplot(data = slice_sample(diamonds, n=1000), mapping = aes(x = carat, y = price, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(shape = 1) # shape is a &quot;static&quot; argument here

gg +
    scale_x_log10() +
    scale_y_log10() +
    labs(x = &#39;Carat&#39;, y = &#39;Price&#39;, col = &#39;Cut quality&#39;) +
    theme_bw()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Here we’ve plotted <code>price</code> by <code>carat</code> and
colored the points according to <code>cut</code>. We then added some
visual modifications on top of the stored plot <code>gg</code>.</p>
<p>Breaking down each of the above instructions, a basic anatomy of most
ggplots is found:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><code>ggplot</code> is the “master” function that sets a “blank
slate.” It is also where the data and aesthetic mapping that is common
to all geoms is specified.</li>
</ol>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot() # totally blank slate</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) # data and the coordinate system</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<ol start="2" style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p><code>geom_*</code> functions add on layers of data. Notice that
these functions also have a <code>data</code> and <code>mapping</code>
argument. These can be used to override these arguments from
<code>ggplot</code> for that geom only.</p></li>
<li><p>Last come any modifications of the existing coordinates or geoms.
This includes <code>scale_*</code>, renaming parts of the plot, and
changing the theme.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>There are many geometries available, and the best way to learn them
is to check out the cheatsheet and try them out on your own data. Rather
than cover them here, we’ll now focus on some common tasks and
challenges.</p>
<div id="facetting" class="section level3">
<h3>Facetting</h3>
<p>Separating data into a group of several plots is done with
<em>facets</em>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>gg_hist &lt;- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, fill = cut)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(cut ~ ., scales = &#39;free&#39;)</code></pre>
<p>An example of a barplot (histogram for discrete variable) with 2d
facetting:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(fill = &#39;lightblue&#39;) +
  facet_grid(cut ~ color, scales = &#39;free&#39;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="changing-color-schemes-and-other-scales" class="section level3">
<h3>Changing color schemes and other scales</h3>
<p>There are tons of different approaches to customizing color with
ggplot, and its easy to get overwhelmed! Here we’ll focus on the
essentials and leave you to research different color palettes or making
your own.</p>
<p>Basically, color is changed through scaling a color aesthetic
(<code>col</code> or <code>fill</code>). Going back to our histogram
example, here we use one of the color palettes provided by
<code>RColorBrewer</code> for discrete variables:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(RColorBrewer)

my_brew_pal &lt;- brewer.pal(8, &#39;Set2&#39;)

gg_hist +
  scale_fill_discrete(type = my_brew_pal)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>As we see above, a color palette can be stored and used in multiple
plots. For presentations or papers, it can be nice to have a set of
specific colors fixed for a variable of interest. An easy way to do this
in ggplot is with <code>scale_*_manual</code>. Say we want all plots
using a mapping with <code>cut</code> to have consistent colors:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>my_pal &lt;- c(&#39;blue2&#39;, &#39;orangered&#39;, &#39;lightpink&#39;, &#39;springgreen&#39;, &#39;gold&#39;)
names(my_pal) &lt;- levels(diamonds$cut)

gg_hist +
  scale_fill_manual(values = my_pal)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(diamonds, aes(price, carat, col = cut)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.1, data = slice_sample(diamonds, prop = 0.1)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  scale_color_manual(values = my_pal) +
  ylim(0, 3)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## `geom_smooth()` using method = &#39;gam&#39; and formula &#39;y ~ s(x, bs = &quot;cs&quot;)&#39;</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: Removed 32 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_point).</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>In general, use <code>scale_*_discrete</code> or
<code>scale_*_continuous</code> if you want to provide existing palettes
or do other scaling functions (we’ll see another use of scale in a
moment), and <code>scale_*_manual</code> for making a discrete palette
by hand.</p>
<p>Aesthetics other than color can be scaled in much the same way. A
common example is the <code>shape</code> aesthetic.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(starwars, aes(eye_color, height, shape = gender)) + # col is continuous here
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(19, 1), na.value = 13) +
  scale_x_discrete(guide = guide_axis(angle = 45))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>diamonds |&gt;
  mutate(car_bin = ifelse(carat &lt; mean(carat), &#39;low_car&#39;, &#39;high_car&#39;)) |&gt;
  group_by(car_bin, color) |&gt;
  summarize(mpr = mean(price)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(color, mpr, shape = car_bin, group = car_bin)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line()</code></pre>
<pre><code>## `summarise()` has grouped output by &#39;car_bin&#39;. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="going-further-1" class="section level3">
<h3>Going further</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>The <a href="https://r-graphics.org/">R Graphics Cookbook</a> has
tons of examples for all things ggplot.</p></li>
<li><p>Chapter 3 in R4DS is a good review of ggplot concepts and basics,
with exercises.</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div id="bonus-intro-to-network-science-with-tidygraph-ggraph" class="section level1">
<h1>Bonus: Intro to Network Science with <code>tidygraph</code> +
<code>ggraph</code></h1>
<p><code>tidygraph</code> is a package for constructing and analyzing
graphs with a workflow similar to tidyr/dplyr, and <code>ggraph</code>
is a package similar to ggplot for visualization.</p>
<p>In tidygraph, a graph is represented with two tibbles: one of nodes
(vertices) and one of edges (links). These tibbles are bundled together
as one object called a <code>tbl_graph</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>(graph &lt;- create_ring(10))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tbl_graph: 10 nodes and 10 edges
## #
## # An undirected simple graph with 1 component
## #
## # Node Data: 10 × 0 (active)
## # … with 4 more rows
## #
## # Edge Data: 10 × 2
##    from    to
##   &lt;int&gt; &lt;int&gt;
## 1     1     2
## 2     2     3
## 3     3     4
## # … with 7 more rows</code></pre>
<p>In ggraph, a graph is plotted in “layers” just like ggplot. There are
specific geoms for nodes and edges:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>gg_net &lt;- ggraph(graph) +
  geom_node_point(color = &#39;blue&#39;, size = 5)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Using `stress` as default layout</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>gg_net # just the nodes</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>gg_net +
  geom_edge_link() # now add the edges on top</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div id="dplyr-verbs-on-graphs" class="section level3">
<h3><code>dplyr</code> verbs on graphs</h3>
<p>Since a <code>tbl_graph</code> is made of tibbles, we can use all the
familiar functions on them:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>graph &lt;- graph |&gt; 
  mutate(name = fruit[1:n()])</code></pre>
<p>Here we see we have added an new <em>attribute</em> to the nodes, by
adding a new column to the nodes tibble. Also, notice how the nodes are
labelled <em>active</em>. This is how we specify whether we want to
manipulate the node or edge tibble. Switch between the two using
<code>activate</code>.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>graph &lt;- graph |&gt; 
  activate(edges) |&gt; 
  mutate(weight = runif(n(), 1, 5))</code></pre>
<div class="info">
<div class="center">
<p><strong>Info</strong></p>
</div>
<p><code>%N&gt;%</code> can be used as shorthand for
<code>|&gt; activate(nodes) |&gt;</code>, and <code>%E&gt;%</code> for
activating edges</p>
</div>
<p>Attributes can be used in aesthetic mappings when plotting. As with
all geoms, check which aesthetics can be controlled with a mapping with
<code>?geom_node_*</code> etc.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggraph(graph) +
  geom_edge_link(mapping = aes(edge_color = weight), edge_width = 2) +
  geom_node_label(mapping = aes(label = name))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Using `stress` as default layout</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="specialized-verbs-on-graphs" class="section level3">
<h3>Specialized verbs on graphs</h3>
<p>In addition to the usual tidyverse functions, there are many new
verbs specific to network science, such as for finding the shortest
distance between two nodes or calculating a node’s degree. These can be
useful, for example, for richer visualization.</p>
<p>In the following example, we generate a network using the famous
Erdős–Rényi model, then compute two measures of <em>node
centrality</em>, or how “connected” a node is. The <em>degree</em> is
the number of neighbors and the <em>page rank</em> is from the formula
for ordering web results in Google’s early days.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>graph &lt;- play_erdos_renyi(300, p = 0.03) |&gt;
  mutate(
    degree = centrality_degree(),
    pagerank = centrality_pagerank()
  )

graph |&gt;
  as_tibble() |&gt;
  pivot_longer(c(degree, pagerank)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(x = value, fill = name)) +
  geom_density() +
  facet_wrap(~name, scales = &#39;free&#39;, nrow = 2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggraph(graph) +
  geom_edge_link0(alpha = 0.05) + # use edge0 family for faster plotting
  geom_node_point(aes(col = degree, size = degree))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Using `stress` as default layout</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>One important type of network operation is <em>clustering</em>, where
group-level patterns are extracted from the data. The basic motive
behind clustering is that nodes within clusters should tend to be more
connected with each other than with nodes of other clusters. Many
different clustering algorithms have been proposed, and tidygraph
supports the most popular ones with the <code>group_*</code>
functions.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>play_islands(n_islands = 5, size_islands = 10, p_within = 0.8, m_between = 3) |&gt; 
  mutate(community = group_fast_greedy()) |&gt; # classic method of maxing modularity
  ggraph() + 
  geom_edge_link(alpha = 0.3) + 
  geom_node_point(aes(color = as.factor(community)), size = 7) + 
  theme_graph() # ggraph&#39;s provided theme: lots of customiziation is available!</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Using `stress` as default layout</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="epidemics-on-networks" class="section level3">
<h3>Epidemics on networks</h3>
<p>To show more <code>tidygraph</code> functionality as part of a more
realistic workflow, we will be implementing a simple stochastic
epidemiological model. Our infection process will spread over a graph
based on two rules.</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>An uninfected, or <em>susceptible</em>, node can become infected
from any neighbor that is infected, independently with probability
<code>beta</code></li>
<li>A node that is already infectious can recover with probability
<code>alpha</code></li>
</ol>
<p>In epidemiological modeling, this model is known as the <em>SIS</em>
model because a node’s state can only go from susceptible to infectious
to susceptible again.</p>
<p>The workhorse behind our implementation will be
<code>tidygraph::map_local</code>, which extracts the neighborhood of
each node as a list of subgraphs, then maps a function <code>.f</code>
over each of these graphs and returns the result. From the function’s
documentation:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The function provided to <code>.f</code> will be called with the
following arguments in addition to those supplied through
<code>...</code>:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>neighborhood</code>: The neighborhood graph of the node</li>
<li><code>graph</code>: The full tbl_graph object</li>
<li><code>node</code>: The index of the node currently mapped over</li>
</ul>
</blockquote>
<p>So, our main task will be to provide an <code>.f</code> that takes
these arguments and updates the infection status of <code>node</code> by
looking at its <code>neighborhood</code> for other infectious nodes.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>init_outbreak &lt;- function(graph, nseed=1) {
    init &lt;- sample(length(graph), nseed)
    
    graph |&gt; 
        mutate(infected = ifelse(node_idx %in% init, TRUE, FALSE))
}

update_node &lt;- function(neighborhood, graph, node, inf_stats, beta = 0.3, alpha = 0.1) {
    if (inf_stats[node]) # if node is already infected, rec. with prob 0.1
        if (runif(1) &lt; alpha) FALSE else TRUE
    
    ninf &lt;- sum(pull(neighborhood, infected)) # get the inf. status of each neighbor
    if (ninf &gt; 0) {
        inter &lt;- runif(ninf)
        if (any(inter &lt; beta)) # pass on infection with ind. probabilities 0.3
            return(TRUE)
    }
    return(FALSE)
}

run_step &lt;- function(graph) {
    graph |&gt; 
        mutate(infected=map_local_lgl(.f = update_node, inf_stat = infected))
}

plot_outbreak &lt;- function(graph) {
    ggraph(graph) +
        geom_edge_link0(alpha = 0.05) +
        geom_node_point(aes(col = infected))
}

graph0 &lt;- create_notable(&quot;Zachary&quot;) |&gt; 
    mutate(node_idx = 1:n()) |&gt; 
    init_outbreak(nseed = 2)

plot_outbreak(graph0) # plot the initial state</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Using `stress` as default layout</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<pre class="r"><code>reduce(1:10, ~run_step(.x), .init = graph0) |&gt;
    plot_outbreak() # plot result after running 10 steps</code></pre>
<pre><code>## Using `stress` as default layout</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="going-further-2" class="section level3">
<h3>Going further</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>A deeper summary of tidygraph’s features can be found <a href="https://www.data-imaginist.com/2017/introducing-tidygraph">here</a></p></li>
<li><p>Something we didn’t get into is the <em>layout</em> of graphs,
and a number of algorithms exist for deciding where to arrange nodes in
a plot. In ggraph you can specify which layout you want with
<code>ggraph(graph, layout = ...)</code>. Many other ways beyond the
“ball and stick” visualization for graphs are also available; see <a href="https://www.data-imaginist.com/2017/ggraph-introduction-layouts/">here</a>
for a good intro.</p></li>
<li><p><code>tidygraph</code> is essentially a wrapper around another
network analysis project called <code>igraph</code>. While igraph itself
is implemented in the C language for speed, an R package also exists. If
you find something that you can’t accomplish using
<code>tidygraph</code>, it is designed to be easy to fall back to using
<code>igraph</code> temporarily.</p></li>
</ul>
<!-- Anything you can do in R's `igraph` can be done in tidygraph, and personally I find the igraph package a bit outdated, but if you don't like the "two-tibble" approach know that another option exists. -->
</div>
